    <title>Japanese Text Analysis and Readability Tools</title>
    <link href="https://krausekai.github.io/en/blog/japanese-text-analysis-and-readability-tools/"/>
    <id>https://krausekai.github.io/en/blog/japanese-text-analysis-and-readability-tools/</id>
    <published>2018-07-26T14:00:00.000Z</published>
    <updated>2025-01-05T19:54:30.943Z</updated>
    
    <summary type="html">
    
      &lt;img class=&quot;banner&quot; alt=&quot;Japanese Text Analysis and Readability Tools&quot; src=&quot;/en/blog/japanese-text-analysis-and-readability-tools/banner.jpg&quot; /&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;vecteezy_disclaimer text-right&quot;&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;p&gt;Learning with content within your difficulty level can save you time, and allow you to actually learn rather than be frustrated with content that is too difficult. The measuring of difficulty is called readability, and the readability of Japanese texts can be determined by three methods: sentence features, kanji grade, and vocabulary lists. Let’s look into these methods and how to use them, from academic to practical.&lt;/p&gt;
    
    </summary>
    
    
